The quantitative concentration of Cys in blood serum was detected under the optimized conditions (Temperature 37 °C). Different concentrations of Cys were added to serum sample and concentration recovered using assembly was lies in the range of 100 to 116% (Table 2
                        ). All these results suggested the potential applicability of synthesized sensor assembly for the determination of Cys in real samples. For the real-time applications, sensor assembly was anticipated for cellular images of endogenous Cys and blood plasma Cys concentration was determined. For this study, HeLa cells were employed for bioimaging potential under confocal laser scanning microscope. Before 24 h of any treatment, an appropriate (1 × 105) numbers of cells were grown in 96 well plates at 37 °C. After successful washing with PBS, treatment of 50 μg/mL of sensor assembly was given for 1 h and washed three times with PBS to remove the extracellular sensor complex. Fluorescence images of cells has been recorded under CLSM after 1 and 2 h of treatment. After 1 h of treatment, orange-yellow emission of HeLa cells specifies the emission arises from the FRET mechanism established between CDs and naphthalimide moiety (Fig. 3
                        ). However, after 2 h of treatment, orange-yellow emission quenched significantly and blue emission was enhanced (Fig. 3B). Blue emission of cells indicates the displacement of CDs from Au nanoparticle surface and FRET mechanism was distorted in the cytoplasm of cells. Specificity of sensor complex towards Cys inside the cells has been predicted by pre-treatment of cells with N-methylmaleimide (NMM). NMM is sulfur reacting chemical entity which reduces the level of Cys in the cytoplasm of cells [54]. No change in the emission of NMM treated cells from orange-yellow to blue confirmed the high selectivity of sensor complex in Cys detection in HeLa cells (Fig. 3C).
